# Wildcard DNS (handled by dnsmasq)
# Additional configuration in /etc/dnsmasq.d/02-homelab-wildcard.conf:
# address=/homelab.local/192.168.40.40
# This routes all *.homelab.local to nginx reverse proxy

# CNAME Records (Aliases)
# Handled in /etc/dnsmasq.d/03-homelab-cnames.conf:
# cname=portal.homelab.local,nginx.homelab.local
# cname=vpn.homelab.local,pfsense.homelab.local
# cname=ntp.homelab.local,pfsense.homelab.local

# Reverse DNS (PTR Records)
# Automatically generated from forward records

# Notes:
# 1. After adding entries, restart Pi-hole DNS: pihole restartdns
# 2. Clear DNS cache on clients: ipconfig /flushdns (Windows) or sudo systemd-resolve --flush-caches (Linux)
# 3. Test resolution: nslookup hostname 192.168.40.35
# 4. Web interface: Settings → Local DNS → DNS Records
# 5. Bulk import: pihole -a addcustomdns IP HOSTNAME

# Best Practices:
# - Use FQDNs (fully qualified domain names) consistently
# - Include short aliases for convenience
# - Document purpose of each entry
# - Keep list organized by function/VLAN
# - Regular audits to remove stale entries
# - Use descriptive hostnames

# Integration:
# - Pi-hole provides DNS for all VLANs
# - pfSense forwards local domain queries to Pi-hole
# - Conditional forwarding ensures consistency
# - DHCP distributes Pi-hole as primary DNS
# - All clients use Pi-hole for resolution

# Security:
# - Local DNS prevents external DNS leaks
# - Controlled name resolution
# - No exposure of internal names to external DNS
# - Monitoring of DNS queries

# Maintenance:
# - Backup this file regularly
# - Version control recommended
# - Test changes before deploying
# - Document changes with comments
# - Coordinate with DHCP static assignments
